##In Wuhan, "half" volunteers perplexed by the epidemic | Wuhan Daily Book 09

WECHAT china30s

Feature description, a platform that encourages you to write about your life. Founded in March 2011, it has a sandwich writing school and a media platform, China Sandwich, at the same time, we are committed to applying the story to cross-border product design, urban culture excavation, exhibition fair, space creation and other three-dimensional field.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Haylin is a freelance dramatist living in Jiyuqiao, Wuhan. In the days leading up to the outbreak, she said that as a native of Wuhan, she was "used to getting up every morning to check on how many new cases there are and so on, and then going to bed at night to see which hospital is sending out a message asking for help. ". To help, she joined a group of volunteers, but felt powerless and at a loss as she helped. The confusion is real.

At a time like this, no one can accuse an ordinary person of powerlessness. When various non-governmental organizations, volunteers, and even the "Rice Circle" give their full support, the furore over the failure of the Red Cross in Hubei Province has not subsided, and the official news that the Shuanghuanglian is out of stock is even funnier.

Haylin's account of her volunteer work, excerpted in today's Wuhan Daily series, has changed over time as her feelings about helping have changed daily. This part of my mind is a part of the real world that was there during the outbreak.

From the beginning of this year's New Year's Day, I pay more attention to the issue of first-line materials. Many family members, friends or relatives of friends are working as nurses and doctors in the front line, but they don't have protective clothing. These messages appear more and more frequently on my wechat account through various channels.

At first I helped people in the group who had met or hadn't met via retweets, but then The Wrong Mans was pulled into a volunteer group to help count supplies.

Although there have been reports on television that efforts are being made to transport and produce supplies, the news from the doctors'emergency shows that supplies are still lagging far behind daily requirements, an increasing number of county hospitals are also issuing distress calls. However, the donation card in the "unified dispatch" policy, goods can not come, or not to use. In addition, in the procurement, easy to cheat the situation is also many.

In the evening, relatives of the family's social worker sent a message to their mother on Wechat saying they were about to collapse. There is so much shopping in the community that they are physically and mentally exhausted from running errands. And now social workers are not covered, and many of their masks are substandard. Earlier, my friend said her social worker friend was going door to door to register a patient with a fever, but there were no surgical masks, only the most sterile cotton ones.

I'm really worried about my friends who are social workers and doctors.

At first, I felt like I wasn't helping much

I spent my first few days on the volunteer team messing around. It is said to be busy, because they want to help and do not seem to actually help what, but still very busy state. The News in the volunteer group is full, the flow is very fast, every day to see the task said to update the hospital material needs information, have resources to connect to the hospital to, and so on.

But what I didn't realize at first was that it was hard to volunteer full time when there were elderly people to take care of and I had a job to do.

A few days ago, I decided to take two or three hours to help, the morning promised to update just sent a few materials on the document information. But the people in the group were faster than me, and she updated my graphite files before I could open them. Then, all of a sudden, someone asked me to take over another follow-up job. I said yes before I knew what was going on. The list of ten hospitals suddenly fell into my hands, and the handover was rushed through on voice mail.

I decided to start with four hospitals that had not yet joined the wechat group that published the latest information on supplies. Each hospital was numbered, and my first contact, Dr. Liu, took my call politely, and after patiently listening to my introduction, she gave me her micro-signal, which was later added and then denied. So I contacted Dr. Xu at the next hospital. Dr. Xu replied slowly, so later contacted the Hospital Logistics Department of the Teacher Shi, the question asked twice, and so on, the two teachers report information is also a bit different, need me to double-check. Some doctors because too busy, not plus Wechat, I will be on the side of the update note information.

So it took an hour to update a few lines of information about a hospital.

However, this was relatively easy. While I was updating the hospital information, suddenly a group of people said that a batch of supplies had arrived. There was an urgent shortage in the hospital in charge (what we call an "urgent shortage" is one that will be completely used up in a day or two) . Hurry up and contact wechat, a shipment. However, I wasn't quite sure how to do this and what messages to send when I did, and missed Deadline.

When my grandmother called me to help, I realized that I might not be the right person for the job.

Later, I joined the The Wrong Mans, because my good friend got a batch of N95 masks to Hangzhou and was worried about how to send them to Hubei by logistics. I'll call it in. The volunteers are in a small group. But after a while of communication, my good friend said because there is no three cards, they can not help, can only suggest to Guangzhou. Several hospitals contacted today all said that N95 is in short supply, and some of them are completely gone! However, I have not yet fully helped her to contact the channel through which she can go. As a conduit for information, I felt deeply powerless.

But the mood in our volunteer group is very high, especially the leader. They've been updating several groups to answer questions, but every time supplies come, they get so excited, they send everyone out to ask the hospital. Our work is still hampered by a lack of visibility and trust, but I believe they will help more and more people.

In the evening, I found a new volunteer to take my place. This work with the hospital on the mobile phone next to the real-time follow-up requirements are relatively high, I do not think I am suitable. And while I feel guilty for stepping down, maybe I can find a better way to help people. For example, by redirecting resources through my contacts, it might be possible to get supplies to a much needed hospital.

Finally, I put together a work guide so that New People who want to do this won't have to cross the river by feeling the same way I did.

As an individual who can't treat a disease, can't drive a car, and has no money, I feel small at the same time as I feel the value of doing what I can. I'm not panicking, I'm not sad, I'm busy. Mom saw that I have been busy with volunteer things, also become a lot calmer, today for the first time did not urge me to eat, rest eyes or sleep.

I've become almost a 24-hour surveillance radar

To tell you the truth, I really don't want to look at my phone these days... but as a Wuhan native, I am used to getting up in the morning to check how many new cases there are and so on, and at night before going to bed to see which hospital is sending a message for help.

I didn't volunteer on Jan. 29, but I also checked the hospital's supply and demand information summary Form, forwarded some requests for help, and told some of my classmates who were working on donations.

The volunteer group had hundreds of messages that they didn't read, and I had no idea where they were or how they were working in general (not without a guide, but with a guide that didn't quite make sense) . And we're too busy to train the new guy, so I think I'm just making it worse. So I narrowed my activities down to just following the two or three people I knew and seeing what they needed and needed.

WECHAT is a powerful platform, but also a less than ideal communication platform. There is no way to solve the communication efficiency problem of online collaboration, I don't know how to participate in helping now, and I don't want to become a full time volunteer who spends all day at the computer, so I feel very lost.

These days I see more and more emergencies in county hospitals. Many people worry that they are not taken care of by Central and private donors. At the same time, I see more and more appeals for help about pneumonia infection but no place to collect it, i had no way of knowing where the message ended up or whether it helped anyone, other than to forward it and follow it up. More and more people are starting to worry about the accuracy of their sources, but I can only think that forwarding is better than not forwarding.

If I could only volunteer for three hours a day, or help someone on the outside to fight an epidemic, what could I do?

But since the lockdown, I've become a 24-hour surveillance radar. I wake up every morning, I open my eyes, and I look at my phone and I see how many new diagnoses there are. During the day, I try to get people who need help to find someone they can help, or I try to get people to ask questions, ask questions, and send out rumors.

Every night to sleep, is the family cry, don't stay up late, I said: "I do things are very important, now very scarce, I have to meet with the owner of the father I know so-and-so. "

To be honest, the panic over the COVID-19 itself only lasted about two or three days, and with the spread of information on the Internet, what I saw more was the plight of doctors facing a large number of patients who were close to mental collapse. The plight of social workers who initially went door-to-door to register high fever patients but did not have protective masks to protect against the virus, the plight of lonely elderly people who had no one to care for them, the plight of sanitation workers who did not have adequate protection, the whole family is infected with the plight of not knowing who will take care of them, the plight of not getting supplies from hospitals, the plight of the Chinese being discriminated against on a large scale abroad, the plight of the donors who purchase supplies who can not find the source of the goods, and the plight of finding the source of the goods and raising the price, the Red Cross is not transparent many people want to donate but are afraid to do so..

In the face of all this, I don't even have time to be angry, except for the occasional curses, I mostly think "I can help who" . So I used to rarely look at my phone, but now I turn the news every day. But I also know that being part of a volunteer team or being a volunteer means giving your life away. So helping out in snippets actually made me feel empty in the end.

I don't know why this feeling came over me, when I was in the shower, when I thought the day was over, I felt a deep emptiness.

I feel like I don't have the right
Go live your life

I feel like I don't have the right

Go live your life

On the last day of January, I actually made a decision not to touch my phone for four hours. Because the eye is already very uncomfortable. Between 3:00 p.m. and 7:00 p.m.

After four hours without a cell phone, the image of the epidemic suddenly seemed to fade and become a mirage in my life. I realized how much I wanted to extend those four hours, live a simple life, drop out of a lot of new material and contacts, and never be sucked out of the world behind the screen again.

But who can do that? The world behind this screen is the real world.

This morning saw the Red Cross assigned to a non-designated Putian Department hospital 18,000 masks, to concord only 3000 people, how can you put down the phone? When I recently contacted a group of British donors, I had a vague sense that they were worried about how to get supplies to a hospital in Wuhan without being intercepted. I repeatedly recommended the UK Federation of schools, which had been tested by the volunteer team and had extensive experience in logistics, but perhaps it was a matter of trust, and they did not communicate further in logistics. On the one hand, I was looking at all the urgent situations in the hospitals listed in the form. On the other hand, the materials far away in the UK were delayed and did not dare to be sent. On the other hand, the leader of the volunteer team sent out a group message saying, "I have a fever. I'm taking a back seat today. " On the other side of the coin are dads who don't know who to trust and are too busy with information from all sides. Every aspect of the delivery of goods requires trust, and that trust has been undermined by scandals and individuals.

The day before yesterday, I was interviewed by a Chinese journalist in London who asked me what I now feel is the most fulfilling message forwarded and helped. I said, probably, that once, I sent a logistics request to a friend, and she forwarded it to another group in which she was a member and replied back to me, "it's done. ".

To see that something has a happy ending, so it's easy to let go. But the sense of accomplishment is really not that much.

Ask for help, with a sense of powerlessness behind, from one group to another you do not know the group, no head, no tail, sometimes I think I did not do anything, more often I think, did better than not do.

The reporter who interviewed me briefly looked at my life and finally said, I think you need to take care of yourself, too. From my point of view, your life is already out of balance.

And I said, "but I feel so guilty and selfish, "and I feel like I don't have the right to live my life and not help people. But I do not really like the volunteers in front of the computer every day from morning to night, so it does not even seem to say the qualification.

Actually, my body is starting to protest a little bit. My stomach hurts every night for a day or two. However, I still don't feel qualified to take care of myself right now. Because the world seems to suddenly have a lot of problems, and then a lot of people are doing more than I do to solve them.

The Fragmented Information Age has cut the world and my life into pieces. And in this torrent of debris, I felt myself fall to pieces. This hollowness, this powerlessness, I don't know if it's a trauma. But I think this is something that many, many people are feeling deeply. It is about the social issues exposed by the epidemic, and philosophical generalizations are meaningless.

If anyone is reading this, I can only say that I hope you are not infected by the negative energy here, I can digest it myself.

After writing the above paragraphs, I shut myself in my room and cried for a while. Then I said to myself: to see the sunny side of life, to see a complete world. No matter what kind of mood, is acceptable, is a part of life.

After sorting out my emotions, I picked up my mobile phone to forward the message as usual, and started the fragmented "volunteer" . In the process of exchanging the message, my friend said the N95 masks that landed in Hangzhou flew to the nearby hospital in Wuhan on the strength of SF in a day or two. On the other side, volunteers in the hospital materials docking group, doctors are increasingly sending messages, to materials. Hope or collapse? However, I feel more and more deeply: Where to find supplies, how to get through the logistics, I know not necessarily more than others know, I know people, not necessarily others have not looked. Perhaps tens of thousands of people these days and all the "Battle of wits" to learn things, far more than I learned, the establishment of contacts, far more useful than all my contacts.

This feeling, so I feel more comfortable, spent some time for themselves.
